    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Right, the timing definitely seems to be the culprit. I'm looking at the code for the state machine transitions now and it all looks logically sound on paper. But when it actually hits production, it's like there's some phantom force causing these tiny, microscopic glitches in the sequence. Does that sound like a legitimate way to describe a race condition, or am I just losing my mind because of the stress?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No, you are not losing your mind; you are describing the very essence of a race condition in a high-concurrency environment. When code looks perfect on paper, but fails in production under load, it usually means the real world—with its unpredictable timing—is exposing a flaw in the assumptions you made about execution order. It's the difference between a perfectly ordered line of marching soldiers and a chaotic rush of a thousand panicked customers trying to get through the same narrow gate at once.\n\nThis \"phantom force\" is just the scheduler deciding when to pause one thread and let another run, and that tiny scheduling decision is enough to trigger a deadlock when multiple threads are fighting over the same limited resources. You need to look for any shared mutable state that isn't protected by a robust, consistent locking mechanism across *all* involved services.",
      "source": "target",
